T1  - Stochastic specification and estimation of share equation systems
AU  - Chavas, Jean-Paul
AU  - Segerson, Kathleen
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 35
IS  - 2
SP  - 337
EP  - 358
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/07/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(87)90032-7
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407687900327
AB  - This paper discusses a theoretical justification for the stochastic specification of singular share equation systems commonly used in the analysis of producer and consumer behavior, which is based on the use of a random objective function. The restrictions on the share equations that are implied by this formulation are derived. In addition, it is shown that in this context additive error terms in share equation models generally can be expected to be heteroskedastic. The issue of invariance of a minimum distance estimator to the equation dropped is also explored.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - OLS or GLS in the presence of specification error?: An expected loss approach
AU  - Thursby, Jerry G.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 35
IS  - 2
SP  - 359
EP  - 374
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/07/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(87)90033-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407687900339
AB  - Omitted variables in regression analysis can lead to the erroneous conclusion that autocorrelation or heteroscedasticity is present. The common response is to use the suggested GLS procedure, even if it is suspected that the error is a non-zero disturbance mean. The question addressed here is whether one is better off with the GLS or with the OLS estimator when the omitted portion of the regression cannot be incorporated into the regression. Using a loss function this paper relates the seriousness of OLS and GLS loss to identifiable parameters. With consistent estimators of these parameters the researcher can choose between OLS and GLS.
ER  - 

