T1  - The application of censored regression techniques to the analysis of tax reform
AU  - Lawrence, David B.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 35
IS  - 2
SP  - 287
EP  - 302
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/07/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(87)90029-7
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407687900297
AB  - This paper applies the techniques of censored regression to both estimate and simulate the behavioral impacts of tax policy on the willingness and ability of taxpayers to take personal deductions on their Federal income tax returns. The estimation of a statistical model for deductible expenditures is a problem of censored regression because if the taxpaying unit does not itemize the dependent variable is not reported. The simulation of personal deductions under tax reform requires recognition that the censoring threshold itself [the zero bracket amount] plays a role in determining the tax savings due to deductibility. Augmenting the behavioral model with an accounting base allows simulation and comparison of the itemization status and tax revenue implications of recent tax reform proposals, including the measure passed by the U.S. Senate in June 1986.
